{"title_page": "Big Cheese (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Big Cheese\n| cover      = File:Nirvana-love-buzz-sub-pop-s.jpg\n| caption    = US picture sleeve\n| alt        =\n| type       = \n| artist     = [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n| album      = [[Bleach (Nirvana album)|Bleach]]\n| A-side     = [[Love Buzz]]\n| released   = November 1988\n| format     = [[vinyl record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = June\u2013September 1988 at [[Reciprocal Recordings]] in [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Grunge]]\n| length     = 3:43\n| label      = [[Sub Pop]]\n| writer     =\n*[[Kurt Cobain]]\n*[[Krist Novoselic]]\n| producer   = [[Jack Endino]]\n}}\n\n'''\"Big Cheese\"''' is a song by the American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], written by vocalist and guitarist [[Kurt Cobain]] and bassist [[Krist Novoselic]]. It was released as the B-side to the band's first single, \"[[Love Buzz]],\" in November 1988. It was re-released as the 12th track on the reissue of their 1989 debut album, ''[[Bleach (Nirvana album)|Bleach]]''.\n\n==Composition==\n\"Big Cheese\" was debuted live on March 19, 1988 at the [[Community World Theatre]] in [[Tacoma, Washington]]. The song was first recorded in the studio in 1988 by [[Jack Endino]] at [[Reciprocal Recording]] in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], during the sessions for what became the band's first single, \"[[Love Buzz]].\" The sessions, which lasted four days over the span of several months, were the band's first with drummer [[Chad Channing]]. The band had originally intended on releasing another song recorded during the sessions, \"Blandest,\" as the single's B-side, but Endino convinced Cobain to use \"Big Cheese\" instead.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Azerrad |first1=Michael |title=Come As You Are: The Story of Nirvana |date=1994 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=0-385-47199-8 |page=82}}</ref> \"It is a much stronger song, and they readily agreed,\" Endino recalled in a February 1997 ''Goldmine'' article by Gillian G. Garr.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garr |first1=Gillian G. |title=Verse Chorus Verse: The Recording History of Nirvana |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Goldmine |date=14 February 1997.}}</ref>\n\nTwo live takes of the song were recorded during a video shoot at the television studio of [[Evergreen State College]] in [[Olympia, Washington]] on March 20, 1990. The full session, which also featured versions of the ''Bleach'' songs \"School\" and \"Floyd the Barber,\" as well as the future ''[[Nevermind]]'' single \"[[Lithium (song)|Lithium]]\", was directed by Jon Snyder and engineered by Greg Babior. It featured a collage of background footage Cobain had taped from television.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garr |first1=Gillian G. |title=Verse Chorus Verse: The Recording History of Nirvana |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Goldmine |date=14 February 1997.}}</ref> \n\nThe final live performance of \"Big Cheese\" was at the [[Melody Ballroom]] in [[Portland, Oregon]] on June 20, 1991.\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n\nAccording to the 1993 Nirvana biography ''[[Come as You Are: The Story of Nirvana|Come As You Are]]'' by [[Michael Azerrad]], \"Big Cheese\" was written about Sub Pop co-founder [[Jonathan Poneman]]. \"I was expressing all the pressures that I felt from him at the time because he was being so judgmental about what we were recording,\" Cobain explained. Azerrad cited the song as evidence of Cobain's gift for turning a specific experience into \"a universal.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Azerrad |authorlink=Michael Azerrad |first1=Michael |title=Come As You Are: The Story of Nirvana |date=1994 |publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] |isbn=0-385-47199-8 |pages=85, 86}}</ref> Author Chris Crisafulli described the song as a \"standard issue anti-authority rant,\" with Cobain complaining about being sent to the office.<ref name=\"Crisafulli\">{{cite book |last1=Crisafulli |first1=Chuck|title=Teen Spirit : The Stories Behind Every Nirvana Song|year=1996|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|page=none}}</ref> The song does not mention Poneman by name or suggest him directly, instead referring to an authority figure named \"Mike.\"\n\nGarr described the song as the more \"trademark grunge\" song on the single, beginning \"with an eerie opening two note guitar wail that explodes into righteousness heaviness.\" <ref name=\"Gaar2009.200\">{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G|title=The Rough Guide to Nirvana |url=https://books.google.com/booksid=i9mvU7iug9AC&pg=PT170&dq=nirvana+hormoaning+even+in+his+youth&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiJy6HEpNzoAhUYr54KHUTmAh4Q6AEwAHoECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=nirvana%20hormoaning%20even%20in%20his%20youth&f=false|date=2009|publisher=[[Rough Guides UK]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n\"Love Buzz\" was the first release in the Sub Pop Singles Club and was limited to 1000 numbered copies. A Sub Pop invoice indicates that 1200 sleeves were made, the other 200 having a red slash instead of a number.\n\nThe release was made \"Single of the Week\" in ''[[Sounds (magazine)|Sounds]]'' by [[John Robb (musician)|John Robb]], which was the first mention of the band in the UK press.\n\nIn 2015, \"Big Cheese\" was listed at number 58 in ''[[Rolling Stone|Rolling Stone's]]'' ''No Apologies: All 102 Nirvana Songs Ranked'' list.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=No Apologies: All 102 Nirvana Songs Ranked |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/no-apologies-all-102-nirvana-songs-ranked-175683/big-cheese-44777/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and release history==\n===Demo and studio versions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date recorded\n! Studio\n! Producer/recorder\n! Releases\n! Personnel\n|-\n| June-September, 1988\n|  [[Reciprocal Recording]], [[Seattle, Washington]] (take one)\n| [[Jack Endino]]\n| Unreleased\n|\n*Kurt Cobain (vocals, guitar)\n*Krist Novoselic (bass guitar)\n*Chad Channing (drums)\n|-\n| June-September, 1988\n|  [[Reciprocal Recording]], [[Seattle, Washington]] (take two)\n| [[Jack Endino]]\n| ''[[Love Buzz]]'' (1988)<br />''[[Bleach (Nirvana album)|Bleach]]'' (1989)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain (vocals, guitar)\n*Krist Novoselic (bass guitar)\n*Chad Channing (drums)\n|-\n| March 20, 1990\n| TV Studio, [[Evergreen State College]], [[Olympia, Washington]]\n| Greg Babior\n| Unreleased\n|\n*Kurt Cobain (vocals, guitar)\n*Krist Novoselic (bass guitar)\n*Chad Channing (drums)\n|}\n\n===Live versions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date recorded\n!Venue\n!Releases\n!Personnel \n|-\n|June 23, 1989\n|[[Rhino Records]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], US \n|''[[With the Lights Out]]'' (DVD) (2004)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain (vocals, guitar)\n*Krist Novoselic (bass)\n*Chad Channing (drums)\n*[[Jason Everman]] (guitar)\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Kurt Cobain]] - guitar, vocals\n* [[Krist Novoselic]] - bass\n* [[Chad Channing]] - drums\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nirvana}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Kurt Cobain]]\n[[Category:1988 debut singles]]\n[[Category:Nirvana (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Sub Pop singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Big Cheese\n| cover      = File:Nirvana-love-buzz-sub-pop-s.jpg\n| caption    = US picture sleeve\n| alt        =\n| type       = \n| artist     = [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n| album      = [[Bleach (Nirvana album)|Bleach]]\n| A-side     = [[Love Buzz]]\n| released   = November 1988\n| format     = [[vinyl record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = June\u2013September 1988 at [[Reciprocal Recordings]] in [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Grunge]]\n| length     = 3:43\n| label      = [[Sub Pop]]\n| writer     =\n*[[Kurt Cobain]]\n*[[Krist Novoselic]]\n| producer   = [[Jack Endino]]\n}}\n\n'''\"Big Cheese\"''' is a song by the American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], written by vocalist and guitarist [[Kurt Cobain]] and bassist [[Krist Novoselic]]. It was released as the B-side to the band's first single, \"[[Love Buzz]],\" in November 1988. It was re-released as the 12th track on the reissue of their 1989 debut album, ''[[Bleach (Nirvana album)|Bleach]]''.\n\n==Composition==\n\"Big Cheese\" was debuted live on March 19, 1988 at the [[Community World Theatre]] in [[Tacoma, Washington]]. The song was first recorded in the studio in 1988 by [[Jack Endino]] at [[Reciprocal Recording]] in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], during the sessions for what became the band's first single, \"[[Love Buzz]].\" The sessions, which lasted four days over the span of several months, were the band's first with drummer [[Chad Channing]]. The band had originally intended on releasing another song recorded during the sessions, \"Blandest,\" as the single's B-side, but Endino convinced Cobain to use \"Big Cheese\" instead.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Azerrad |first1=Michael |title=Come As You Are: The Story of Nirvana |date=1994 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=0-385-47199-8 |page=82}}</ref> \"It is a much stronger song, and they readily agreed,\" Endino recalled in a February 1997 ''Goldmine'' article by Gillian G. Garr.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garr |first1=Gillian G. |title=Verse Chorus Verse: The Recording History of Nirvana |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Goldmine |date=14 February 1997.}}</ref>\n\nTwo live takes of the song were recorded during a video shoot at the television studio of [[Evergreen State College]] in [[Olympia, Washington]] on March 20, 1990. The full session, which also featured versions of the ''Bleach'' songs \"School\" and \"Floyd the Barber,\" as well as the future ''[[Nevermind]]'' single \"[[Lithium (song)|Lithium]]\", was directed by Jon Snyder and engineered by Greg Babior. It featured a collage of background footage Cobain had taped from television.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garr |first1=Gillian G. |title=Verse Chorus Verse: The Recording History of Nirvana |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Goldmine |date=14 February 1997.}}</ref> \n\nThe final live performance of \"Big Cheese\" was at the [[Melody Ballroom]] in [[Portland, Oregon]] on June 20, 1991.\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n\nAccording to the 1993 Nirvana biography ''[[Come As You Are]]'' by [[Michael Azerrad]], \"Big Cheese\" was written about Sub Pop co-founder [[Jonathan Poneman]]. \"I was expressing all the pressures that I felt from him at the time because he was being so judgmental about what we were recording,\" Cobain explained. Azerrad cited the song as evidence of Cobain's gift for turning a specific experience into \"a universal.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Azerrad |authorlink=Michael Azerrad |first1=Michael |title=Come As You Are: The Story of Nirvana |date=1994 |publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] |isbn=0-385-47199-8 |pages=85, 86}}</ref> Author Chris Crisafulli described the song as a \"standard issue anti-authority rant,\" with Cobain complaining about being sent to the office.<ref name=\"Crisafulli\">{{cite book |last1=Crisafulli |first1=Chuck|title=Teen Spirit : The Stories Behind Every Nirvana Song|year=1996|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|page=none}}</ref> The song does not mention Poneman by name or suggest him directly, instead referring to an authority figure named \"Mike.\"\n\nGarr described the song as the more \"trademark grunge\" song on the single, beginning \"with an eerie opening two note guitar wail that explodes into righteousness heaviness.\" <ref name=\"Gaar2009.200\">{{cite book|last1=Gaar|first1=Gillian G|title=The Rough Guide to Nirvana |url=https://books.google.com/booksid=i9mvU7iug9AC&pg=PT170&dq=nirvana+hormoaning+even+in+his+youth&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiJy6HEpNzoAhUYr54KHUTmAh4Q6AEwAHoECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=nirvana%20hormoaning%20even%20in%20his%20youth&f=false|date=2009|publisher=[[Rough Guides UK]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n\"Love Buzz\" was the first release in the Sub Pop Singles Club and was limited to 1000 numbered copies. A Sub Pop invoice indicates that 1200 sleeves were made, the other 200 having a red slash instead of a number.\n\nThe release was made \"Single of the Week\" in ''[[Sounds (magazine)|Sounds]]'' by [[John Robb (musician)|John Robb]], which was the first mention of the band in the UK press.\n\nIn 2015, \"Big Cheese\" was listed at number 58 in ''[[Rolling Stone|Rolling Stone's]]'' ''No Apologies: All 102 Nirvana Songs Ranked'' list.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=No Apologies: All 102 Nirvana Songs Ranked |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/no-apologies-all-102-nirvana-songs-ranked-175683/big-cheese-44777/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and release history==\n===Demo and studio versions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date recorded\n! Studio\n! Producer/recorder\n! Releases\n! Personnel\n|-\n| June-September, 1988\n|  [[Reciprocal Recording]], [[Seattle, Washington]] (take one)\n| [[Jack Endino]]\n| Unreleased\n|\n*Kurt Cobain (vocals, guitar)\n*Krist Novoselic (bass guitar)\n*Chad Channing (drums)\n|-\n| June-September, 1988\n|  [[Reciprocal Recording]], [[Seattle, Washington]] (take two)\n| [[Jack Endino]]\n| ''[[Love Buzz]]'' (1988)<br />''[[Bleach (Nirvana album)|Bleach]]'' (1989)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain (vocals, guitar)\n*Krist Novoselic (bass guitar)\n*Chad Channing (drums)\n|-\n| March 20, 1990\n| TV Studio, [[Evergreen State College]], [[Olympia, Washington]]\n| Greg Babior\n| Unreleased\n|\n*Kurt Cobain (vocals, guitar)\n*Krist Novoselic (bass guitar)\n*Chad Channing (drums)\n|}\n\n===Live versions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date recorded\n!Venue\n!Releases\n!Personnel \n|-\n|June 23, 1989\n|[[Rhino Records]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], US \n|''[[With the Lights Out]]'' (DVD) (2004)\n|\n*Kurt Cobain (vocals, guitar)\n*Krist Novoselic (bass)\n*Chad Channing (drums)\n*[[Jason Everman]] (guitar)\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n* 